{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778184279,"nonce":"xDDVBZCcceh1PmhZSfoHlAOSo4o=","title":"D_z feedthrough: compute correctly for sensory_noise / structural_da × qr_cost (not zeroed)","message":"In `src/rlrmp/analysis/induced_gain.py`, the `_qr_cost_Cz_Dz` helper conservatively zeroes the `D_z` matrix for non-`additive_force` w-channels. This is mathematically incorrect (an underestimate); it was a scoping shortcut, not a necessity.\n\nFor `sensory_noise × qr_cost`: sensory perturbation `w` enters the controller's observation at time `t`; controller produces `u_t` from that observation in the same timestep; qr_cost output `z_t = sqrt(R)·u_t` thus has a direct dependence `∂z/∂w = sqrt(R)·∂u/∂obs·∂obs/∂w = sqrt(R)·∂u/∂obs` (for `obs = sensor + w`, `∂obs/∂w = I`). One Jacobian, autodiff'able.\n\nFor `structural_da × qr_cost`: similar same-timestep path through the small-gain auxiliary output. The exact form depends on how `B_w` is defined for the small-gain auxiliary loop; document and compute correctly.\n\n**Fix:**\n1. Update `_qr_cost_Cz_Dz` to compute `D_z` via JAX autodiff for both `sensory_noise` and `structural_da` channels.\n2. Add a test to `tests/test_induced_gain.py` confirming the non-headline channels give a *higher* gain after the fix (since the previous zero-feedthrough was an underestimate).\n3. Update the docstring describing what `D_z` represents and remove the \"conservatively zeroed\" caveat.\n4. Also rename the `sensory_noise` channel to `sensory_perturbation` — H∞ doesn't distinguish stochastic noise from deterministic L₂-bounded perturbation, and the existing rlrmp feedback-perturbation analysis is exactly this channel pair. Channel sentinel renames: `W_SENSORY_NOISE → W_SENSORY_PERTURBATION` (keep the old name as a deprecated alias for one cycle if it's referenced externally).\n\nSurfaced from analyser landing review (`74bfd86`).","files":null}]}